		<title>New Gestures: The Blackberry Z10</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/new-gestures-the-blackberry-z10</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/new-gestures-the-blackberry-z10#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 09 Aug 2013 12:55:49 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Debbie Abernathy]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Contributor's Corner]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Mobile]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Blackberry]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=783</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/new-gestures-the-blackberry-z10"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/bb-z10-i1-620x465-300x225.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="bb-z10-i1-620x465" title="" /></a>by: Debbie Abernathy Recently, Blackberry released the newest addition to the BB family: the Blackberry Z10. While the newest BB model is a major step up in many ways, one of its trademark features is Gestures, an interesting and efficient way to use the interface of your phone.  Let’s take a closer look at the new gestures for the Blackberry Z10. Pros: The Blackberry Hub The Hub may be one of the most popular additions to the Blackberry OS. Also called the “peek[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><strong><em>by: Debbie Abernathy</em></strong></p>
<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/bb-z10-i1-620x465.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-793" alt="bb-z10-i1-620x465" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/bb-z10-i1-620x465-300x225.jpg" width="300" height="225" /></a></p>
<p>Recently, Blackberry released the newest addition to the BB family: the Blackberry Z10. While the newest BB model is a major step up in many ways, one of its trademark features is Gestures, an interesting and efficient way to use the interface of your phone.  Let’s take a closer look at the new gestures for the <a title="Blackberry Z10" href="http://ph.blackberry.com/smartphones/blackberry-z10.html" target="_blank">Blackberry Z10</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Pros: The Blackberry Hub</strong></p>
<p>The Hub may be one of the most popular additions to the Blackberry OS. Also called the “peek feature”, it is designed to make the interface more efficient and allows the  user to see all notifications with a quick swipe upward across the screen. That way, whenever that little red light comes on at the top of the phone, you won’t have to scroll through rows of apps to find your notification. Instead, just swipe upward to see if there’s anything new on your Facebook, Twitter, Tumblr or BBM. You can also get notifications from other programs, like text messages, email and updates from your calendars. It’s quick, easy and addictively efficient.</p>
<p><strong>Moving Around Between Apps, and More</strong></p>
<p>And that isn’t all. There are many other gestures you can use. For example, you can use a sliding motion across the screen from left to right to progress through a song or turn the page of an eBook. You can also zoom in or out using two fingers in the center of the screen. Also, to minimize apps for multitasking, just use an upward swiping motion to return to the home screen to select something else. If you need to change the settings, show the menus in any app by swiping downward. Finally, to show the keyboard, use two fingers to swipe upward.</p>
<p><strong>The Cons: Is It Too Complicated?</strong></p>
<p>On their own, these gestures don’t seem too bad, but trying to remember them all at once could get a bit more complicated. In fact, this is one drawback that users who previously operated on Android or iOS report. However, it may just take some time to get used to the new interface. Change is good, right?</p>
<p><strong>Other Features</strong></p>
<p>In addition to the new Gestures, the BB Z10 also comes with an 8-megapixel camera and Time Shift software to make minimal edits to create the best photos. Blackberry Messenger now offers Screen Share, which allows you to share whatever is on your screen with whoever you are calling, which can be a convenient way to share material with colleagues if you are working remotely. The phone also comes with a software keyboard, as opposed to earlier models that featured a physical keyboard. Overall, the Z10 offers a sleeker, more streamlined smartphone experience.</p>
<p>What do you think &#8211; do you love or loathe the new Z10? Let us know in the comments below.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/new-gestures-the-blackberry-z10 font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
