		<item>
		<title>Making anchors work on Facebook Applications</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/making-anchors-work-on-facebook-applications</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/making-anchors-work-on-facebook-applications#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 19 Nov 2011 14:04:08 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook application]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[HTML 5]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[JavaScript]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[jQuery]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Nestlé-MINISTOP Match and Dash]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=676</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/making-anchors-work-on-facebook-applications"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/facebook-apps-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="Facebook Application" /></a>With iframes, Facebook applications get to take advantage of the powerful web technologies to come up with stunning features using JavaScript (or jQuery for that matter), HTML 5 and so on. While these days they are iframe-based, there are few things that will not work on Facebook applications as they normally do in normal web pages. One of these is named anchors which are used in creating bookmarks within the HTML document. If named anchor matters to your app given[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/facebook-apps.jpg"><img class="aligncenter" title="Facebook Application" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/facebook-apps.jpg" alt="" width="225" height="225" /></a></p>
<p>With iframes, Facebook applications get to take advantage of the powerful web technologies to come up with stunning features using JavaScript (or jQuery for that matter), HTML 5 and so on. While these days they are iframe-based, there are few things that will not work on Facebook applications as they normally do in normal web pages. One of these is named anchors which are used in creating bookmarks within the HTML document.</p>
<p>If named anchor matters to your app given that Facebook doesn&#8217;t allow it, you are to find a perfect alternative for it &#8211; something that would mimic its behavior. You may think of JavaScript scroll functions as candidates. A number of jQuery plugins are also available for a sophisticated execution of scroll functions running on top of JavaScript.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, neither Javascript native scroll functions nor those jQuery plugins work on FB apps despite the fact that they are iframe-based. Good news is Facebook JavaScript SDK provides a scroll function to compensate the lack of support to named anchors.</p>
<p><em>FB.Canvas.scrollTo(x,y);</em></p>
<p>where <em>x</em> and <em>y</em> are the horizontal and vertical scroll position respectively. This function should be used in conjunction with <em>FB.Canvas.setSize</em> and <em>FB.Canvas.setAutoResize</em>.</p>
<p><strong>Sample</strong>:</p>
<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/nestle-ministop-match-and-dash.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-677" title="nestle-ministop-match-and-dash" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/nestle-ministop-match-and-dash-300x199.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="199" /></a></p>
<p><a href="http://apps.facebook.com/matchanddash" target="_blank">Nestlé-MINISTOP Match and Dash</a> is a sample working Facebook Application implementing the FB.Canvas.scrollTo() function. Just go to the app&#8217;s <a href="https://apps.facebook.com/matchanddash/mechanics.php" target="_blank">mechanics</a> page and click on the &#8216;More Info&#8217; button.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/making-anchors-work-on-facebook-applications font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/making-anchors-work-on-facebook-applications/feed</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>1</slash:comments>
		</item>
		<item>
		<title>Apple rolls out iOS 5.0.1 update</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/apple-rolls-out-ios-5-0-1-update</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/apple-rolls-out-ios-5-0-1-update#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 11 Nov 2011 23:55:44 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Mobile]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Softwares]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Apple]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[iOS]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[iOS 5]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[iTunes]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=661</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/apple-rolls-out-ios-5-0-1-update"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/hero20110302-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="iOS 5.0.1" title="iOS 5.0.1" /></a>Roughly a month after the release of the major upgrade to the mobile operating system (iOS 5) by Apple, the consumer electronics giant is rolling out the firmware update to its devices currently running iOS 5 (Click here to read related post). iOS 5.0.1, which addresses battery life woes and bug fixes was reportedly seeded to developers and select end-users who complained about the battery life issue on their iOS devices. The firmware update contains improvements and other bug fixes[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/hero20110302-300x85.jpg"><img class="aligncenter" title="iOS 5.0.1" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/hero20110302-300x85.jpg" alt="iOS 5.0.1" width="300" height="85" /></a></p>
<p>Roughly a month after the release of the major upgrade to the mobile operating system (iOS 5) by Apple, the consumer electronics giant is rolling out the firmware update to its devices currently running iOS 5 (Click <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/apple-finally-releases-ios-5">here </a>to read related post). iOS 5.0.1, which addresses battery life woes and bug fixes was reportedly seeded to developers and select end-users who complained about the battery life issue on their iOS devices.</p>
<p>The firmware update contains improvements and other bug fixes including:</p>
<ul>
<li>Fixes bugs affecting battery life</li>
<li> Adds Multitasking Gestures for original iPad</li>
<li>Resolves bugs with Documents in the Cloud</li>
<li>Improves voice recognition for Australian users using dictation</li>
</ul>
<div>Apple devices made compatible with the latest update include:</div>
<div>
<ul>
<li>iPhone 4S</li>
<li>iPhone 4</li>
<li>iPad 2</li>
<li>iPad</li>
<li>iPod touch (4th generation)</li>
<li>iPod touch (3rd generation)</li>
</ul>
<div>The software update can be downloaded either through iTunes or over-the-air (OTA) and is 777.8MB in filesize.</div>
</div>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/apple-rolls-out-ios-5-0-1-update font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
