		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-fix-cufon-issue-on-internet-explorer-9</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-fix-cufon-issue-on-internet-explorer-9#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 23 Oct 2011 11:07:17 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Softwares]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Cufon]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Internet Explorer]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[JavaScript]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=652</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-fix-cufon-issue-on-internet-explorer-9"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/internet-explorer-9-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="internet-explorer-9" /></a>Cufon enables web pages of today to use custom fonts unlike before where websites are limited to the fonts available for the web and are forced to use images instead for labels or headers that use non-web fonts. Web developers can now use non-standard web fonts to web pages and applications, thanks to the open-source JavaScript libraries freely available over the internet like Cufon. However, it&#8217;s odd that Cufon doesn&#8217;t work properly with the latest version of Microsoft&#8217;s web browser[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/internet-explorer-9.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-655" title="internet-explorer-9" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/internet-explorer-9.jpg" alt="" width="204" height="204" /></a></p>
<p>Cufon enables web pages of today to use custom fonts unlike before where websites are limited to the fonts available for the web and are forced to use images instead for labels or headers that use non-web fonts. Web developers can now use non-standard web fonts to web pages and applications, thanks to the open-source JavaScript libraries freely available over the internet like Cufon.</p>
<p>However, it&#8217;s odd that Cufon doesn&#8217;t work properly with the latest version of Microsoft&#8217;s web browser &#8211; Internet Explorer 9 though it works on IE 8, IE 7 and even with the most hated browser by web developers (IE 6). John Hvartin, Program Manager for Internet Explorer explains why older (pre 1.09i) versions of Cufon don’t work correctly with IE9 on a blog.</p>
<p>&#8220;The library depended on legacy, non-standard IE behavior fixed in IE9 . The IE9 behavior is correct (as in, IE9 now behaves like all other browsers) and won’t change so we’ve worked with the Cufon authors on a fix for the library. And as we find sites affected by this, we contact them to let them know there’s an updated version of Cufon to use.</p>
<p>The gory details…</p>
<p>Cufon chooses an “engine” for rendering in registerEngine:</p>
<pre class="brush: plain; title: ; notranslate">Cufon.registerEngine(&quot;vml&quot;, (function () {
    if (!document.namespaces) { //&amp;lt;------ browser detection
        return
    }
   // build engine...
}</pre>
<p>The check for <code>document.namespaces</code> is effectively an “if IE” check. IE supports <code>document.namespaces</code>, so the ‘vml’ engine is used instead of the ‘canvas’ engine. IE9 supports VML so that alone isn’t the problem. However, the ‘vml’ engine depends on legacy IE behavior in two places:</p>
<ol>
<li>Cufon uses elem.unknownAttr = ‘value’ to set a unknown attribute, e.g.
<pre class="brush: plain; title: ; notranslate">            S.stroked = &quot;f&quot;;
            S.coordsize = m;
            S.coordorigin = H = (q - o) + &quot;,&quot; + p;
            S.path = (Z.d ? &quot;m&quot; + Z.d + &quot;xe&quot; : &quot;&quot;) + &quot;m&quot; + H + e;
            S.fillcolor = a;</pre>
<p>Unlike IE8 , IE9 treats these as script expando properties and not content attributes. If you replace these assignments with the standards-based <code>setAttribute(A, B)</code>, it will work correctly.</li>
<li>Cufon omits the unit ‘px’ in setting style properties, like ‘width’ and ‘height’. Like other browsers, IE9 requires units on length values without unit.</li>
</ol>
<p>While this gets the VML engine working in IE9 , the best solution is using the latest-and-greatest: canvas. The canvas engine works great in IE9&#8243; .</p>
<p><strong>Solution</strong>:</p>
<p>Add this code inside the &lt;head&gt; tag of your web page:</p>
<pre class="brush: plain; title: ; notranslate">&lt;meta content=&quot;IE=8&quot; http-equiv=&quot;X-UA-Compatible&quot; /&gt;</pre>
<p>Or</p>
<pre class="brush: plain; title: ; notranslate">&lt;!--[if gte IE 9]&gt; &lt;script type=&quot;text/javascript&quot;&gt; Cufon.set('engine', 'canvas'); &lt;/script&gt; &lt;![endif]--&gt;</pre>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-fix-cufon-issue-on-internet-explorer-9 font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-fix-cufon-issue-on-internet-explorer-9/feed</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>1</slash:comments>
		</item>
