		<title>How to customize notification ringtone of your Android device</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-customize-notification-ringtone-of-your-android-device</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-customize-notification-ringtone-of-your-android-device#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 08 Oct 2011 15:39:05 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Mobile]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Softwares]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Android]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[notification ringtone]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=634</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-customize-notification-ringtone-of-your-android-device"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/android_logo-150x150.gif" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="android_logo" /></a>If you are in the process of exploring your new Android device, chances are you will get frustrated because you will not be able to change your notification tone to your preferred sound file. Android devices don&#8217;t offer an option to select a custom ringtone for your notifications as normal mobile phones do.  By default, they just present a list of predefined tones for you to choose from which you can set by going to your device&#8217;s Settings &#62; Sound[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/android_logo.gif"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-637" title="android_logo" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/android_logo-300x225.gif" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a></p>
<p>If you are in the process of exploring your new Android device, chances are you will get frustrated because you will not be able to change your notification tone to your preferred sound file. Android devices don&#8217;t offer an option to select a custom ringtone for your notifications as normal mobile phones do.  By default, they just present a list of predefined tones for you to choose from which you can set by going to your device&#8217;s Settings &gt; Sound &gt; Notification ringtone.</p>
<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/notification-ringtone.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-635" title="notification-ringtone" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/notification-ringtone-180x300.png" alt="" width="180" height="300" /></a></p>
<p>For typical users, this might cause them to think that there&#8217;s no way their device can have a notification ringtone of their choice and just be contented with what is currently available. A fact not applicable to the tech-savvy ones who will definitely find resources to figure out how things go for their &#8220;droids&#8221;. The question is : Is it possible?</p>
<p>It might not be as simple as how you do it on average mobile devices but yes, it is possible to set a custom tone for Androids. Simply copy the desired audio file to this directory of your Android device:</p>
<p><strong>/mnt/sdcard/media/audio/notifications</strong></p>
<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/notifications-folder.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-636" title="notifications-folder" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/notifications-folder-180x300.png" alt="" width="180" height="300" /></a></p>
<p>After that you will now be able to select the files you copied to this folder from the list of available notification ringtones.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-customize-notification-ringtone-of-your-android-device font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-customize-notification-ringtone-of-your-android-device/feed</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>2</slash:comments>
		</item>
		<item>
		<title>How to clear cached data of pages shared on Facebook</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-clear-cached-data-of-pages-shared-on-facebook</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-clear-cached-data-of-pages-shared-on-facebook#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 20 Sep 2011 16:40:38 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook cache]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook share]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook url linter]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=627</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-clear-cached-data-of-pages-shared-on-facebook"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/facebook-apps-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="Facebook URL Linter" /></a>Sharing links on Facebook is one of the most frequently used feature of the popular social networking site. This enables users to share all sorts of web pages in just a couple of seconds to their Facebook friends. However, URLs that were already shared on Facebook are cached so that the page preview will load faster the next time they are shared again. This may sound great to those sharing the URL but not to the page owner as updates[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/facebook-apps.jpg"><img class="aligncenter" title="Facebook URL Linter" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/facebook-apps.jpg" alt="" width="225" height="225" /></a></p>
<p>Sharing links on Facebook is one of the most frequently used feature of the popular social networking site. This enables users to share all sorts of web pages in just a couple of seconds to their Facebook friends. However, URLs that were already shared on Facebook are cached so that the page preview will load faster the next time they are shared again. This may sound great to those sharing the URL but not to the page owner as updates to the site description, thumbnail image and title are not reflected instantly when the page is shared because Facebook fetches the cached data of that page not the latest version.</p>
<p>There are two possible ways on how to get this problem fixed. Depending on what method will be most convenient to you, you can use either of the following:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Appending query string to the page being shared</strong>. Facebook treats every URL that are not exactly the same as different pages. This is true to all pages even when the URLs point to the same web file within a server and of the same domain. For example, http://yourdomain.com/index.php and http://yourdomain.com/index.php?rand=1 are two different pages for Facebook. Similarly,  http://yourdomain.com/index.php?rand=1 is not the same as http://yourdomain.com/index.php?rand=2. Therefore, sharing the page with different query string values will result to showing the latest version of the page to be displayed. This will become some sort of an issue if you are tracking the number of times the URL was shared because they&#8217;re counted as two separate pages.</li>
</ol>
<ol start="2">
<li><strong>Facebook URL Linter</strong>. This is a tool from Facebook that checks a page for possible markup errors and gives you an idea of the data to be displayed once it&#8217;s shared on Facebook. This includes the title, description and the thumbnail image. Using this tool to pages that have already been shared in the past will be force Facebook to retrieve the current version of the URL being shared as it updates the cached data. As a result, you will no longer have to append ugly query strings to your shared page just to have Facebook show the latest version and this, by far, is the best solution to Facebook cache.<br />
<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Facebook-URL-Linter.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-630" title="Facebook URL Linter" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Facebook-URL-Linter-300x148.png" alt="" width="300" height="148" /></a></p>
<p>Facebook URL Linter can be accessed <a href="http://developers.facebook.com/tools/lint/" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>
</ol>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-clear-cached-data-of-pages-shared-on-facebook font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
