		<title>Mozilla to release Firefox for tablets soon</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/mozilla-to-release-firefox-for-tablets-soon</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/mozilla-to-release-firefox-for-tablets-soon#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 03 Sep 2011 13:17:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Mobile]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Softwares]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Android]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Firefox]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[tablets]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[web browser]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=608</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/mozilla-to-release-firefox-for-tablets-soon"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/firefox-android-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="firefox-android" /></a>Mozilla, the company behind one of the most popular web browsers today, is reportedly working on a new version of Firefox that is optimized for tablet PCs. A mobile version of Firefox released recently runs seamlessly on smartphones with Google&#8217;s Android OS with full Adobe Flash Player support. The new version, which is currently under development, will be an enhancement of its phone-based predecessor taking advantage of the tablets&#8217; wide screen resolution. According to Ian Barlow, Mozilla User Interface (UI) Designer,[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a title="Firefox for tablets" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/firefox-android.jpg" rel="lightbox"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-609" title="firefox-android" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/firefox-android.jpg" alt="" width="225" height="225" /></a></p>
<p>Mozilla, the company behind one of the most popular web browsers today, is reportedly working on a new version of Firefox that is optimized for tablet PCs. A mobile version of Firefox released recently runs seamlessly on smartphones with Google&#8217;s Android OS with full Adobe Flash Player support. The new version, which is currently under development, will be an enhancement of its phone-based predecessor taking advantage of the tablets&#8217; wide screen resolution.</p>
<p>According to Ian Barlow, Mozilla User Interface (UI) Designer, talks about the new version of Firefox they are working on.</p>
<p>&#8220;Firefox looks right at home on Android 3.0, drawing its overall theme from Honeycomb’s minimalist design language. Of course, this is still Firefox, so we’ve made sure to keep familiar visual elements in place, like our signature big back button and a distinctive tab shape.&#8221;</p>
<p>The Awesomebar which allows quick access to bookmarks, history, and synced desktop activity is also included as one of the main features of the tablet-based Mozilla Firefox.</p>
<p>The bigger screen size of tablets enable the developers to bring some helpful browsing elements, like tabs, back which were tucked away from the Firefox for phones.</p>
<p>&#8220;In landscape mode, tabs exist in a persistent left bar, allowing for quicker browsing. You can switch through tabs with your left thumb, and scroll through web content with your right. In portrait mode, this tab bar gets rolled up into a menu item at the top of the screen, to free up browsing space below. So whether you like keeping lots of tabs open and quickly switching back and forth between them, or if you prefer to just open a page and see nothing else on the screen, Firefox has you covered.&#8221;</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/mozilla-to-release-firefox-for-tablets-soon font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/mozilla-to-release-firefox-for-tablets-soon/feed</wfw:commentRss>
