		<category><![CDATA[WSDL]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=576</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-connecting-to-a-web-service"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="" /></a>The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), an international community that develops web standards, defines a web service to be a software system designed to support interoperable machine-to-machine interaction over a network. It has an interface described in a machine-processable format (specifically Web Services Description Language or WSDL). Web Services are application components running on a web server enabling other applications residing within the same or on a different remote server  to &#8220;consume&#8221; them. Since web services are based on XML[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a title="PHP Snippets: Connecting to a Web Service" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" rel="lightbox"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" alt="" width="184" height="113" /></a></p>
<p>The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), an international community that develops web standards, defines a web service to be a software system designed to support interoperable machine-to-machine interaction over a network. It has an interface described in a machine-processable format (specifically Web Services Description Language or WSDL). Web Services are application components running on a web server enabling other applications residing within the same or on a different remote server  to &#8220;consume&#8221; them. Since web services are based on XML and HTTP platforms, system and language interoperability is made possible over a network.</p>
<p>The following are the platform elements of a web service:</p>
<ul>
<li>SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol), a protocol for accessing a Web Service</li>
<li>UDDI (Universal Description, Discovery and Integration), an XML-based language for locating and describing Web services</li>
<li>WSDL (Web Services Description Language), a directory service where companies can register and search for Web services</li>
</ul>
<p>Uses of Web Services:</p>
<ul>
<li>Makes application components reusable because it drops the need of having to code them over again in some other platforms</li>
<li>Provides a way of exchanging data to and from different platforms</li>
</ul>
<p>Various web programming languages running under different machines provide different ways of connecting to and consuming a web service. Usually, an OOP language provides system-defined class containing necessary methods for web service consumption. PHP, for instance, has the <a href="http://www.php.net/manual/en/class.soapclient.php" target="_blank">SoapClient</a> class providing methods to call a specific function exposed by the web service, list all available methods and so on.</p>
<p>The following PHP code snippet shows how to connect to a web service:</p>
<pre class="brush: php; title: ; notranslate">
$client = new SoapClient(&quot;http://domain.com/wservices.asmx?wsdl&quot;, array('login'          =&gt; &quot;USERNAME&quot;,
                                                                        'password'       =&gt; &quot;PASSWORD&quot;));
$param = array(&quot;param_name&quot; =&gt; $param_value);
$response = $client-&gt;__call(&quot;MethodName&quot;, array(&quot;parameters&quot; =&gt; $param));
echo &quot;&lt;pre&gt;&quot;;
print_r($response);
echo &quot;&lt;/pre&gt;&quot;;
</pre>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-connecting-to-a-web-service font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
