		<title>Describing Microsoft SQL Server table structure</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/describing-microsof-sql-server-table-structure</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/describing-microsof-sql-server-table-structure#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 18 Jun 2011 00:53:48 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Softwares]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[describe table]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Microsoft]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Microsoft SQL Server]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=568</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/describing-microsof-sql-server-table-structure"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/MS-SQL-Server-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="MS-SQL-Server" /></a>In order to work effectively with an existing database, it is a must for developers to know the structure of the database objects they are working with. Database Management Systems provide different ways on how to do it. This post focuses on describing an MS SQL Server table using sp_columns which retrieves column information for the specified tables or views that can be queried in the current environment. The Syntax: Sample Usage: The example above return all field information for[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/MS-SQL-Server.jpg" rel="lightbox" title="Microsoft SQL Server"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-569" title="MS-SQL-Server" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/MS-SQL-Server.jpg" alt="" width="284" height="177" /></a></p>
<p>In order to work effectively with an existing database, it is a must for developers to know the structure of the database objects they are working with. Database Management Systems provide different ways on how to do it. This post focuses on describing an MS SQL Server table using <em>sp_columns</em> which retrieves column information for the specified tables or views that can be queried in the current environment.</p>
<p>The Syntax:</p>
<pre class="brush: plain; title: ; notranslate">
sp_columns [ @table_name = ] object  [ , [ @table_owner = ] owner ]
     [ , [ @table_qualifier = ] qualifier ]
     [ , [ @column_name = ] column ]
     [ , [ @ODBCVer = ] ODBCVer ]
</pre>
<p>Sample Usage:</p>
<pre class="brush: plain; title: ; notranslate">
exec sp_columns TableName
</pre>
<p>The example above return all field information for table <em>TableName</em>. If you want to return the structure of a specific table field, you have it like this:</p>
<pre class="brush: plain; title: ; notranslate">
exec sp_columns TableName, @column_name = 'column_name'
</pre>
<p>or</p>
<pre class="brush: plain; title: ; notranslate">
exec sp_columns TableName, @column_name = '%column_name%'
</pre>
<p>if you want to perform a wildcard search.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/describing-microsof-sql-server-table-structure font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/describing-microsof-sql-server-table-structure/feed</wfw:commentRss>
