		<title>PHP Snippets: Converting XML to array</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-converting-xml-to-array</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-converting-xml-to-array#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 11 Jun 2011 03:01:49 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP Snippets]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[XML]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[XML to array]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=531</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-converting-xml-to-array"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="PHP" /></a>XML or Extensible Markup Language is now being used widely by developers in transporting and storing data. This can be useful in returning a response to an Asynchronous Javascript and XML (AJAX) request, RSS feed, or in passing complex data to and from a web application. Parsing XML data varies from language to language. In JavaScript, for instance, XML data are parsed by creating an instance of ActiveXObject for Internet Explorer or XMLHttpRequest otherwise. An effective way of doing so[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="PHP" rel="lightbox" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png"><img class="aligncenter" title="PHP" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" alt="" width="184" height="113" /></a></p>
<p>XML or Extensible Markup Language is now being used widely by developers in transporting and storing data. This can be useful in returning a response to an Asynchronous Javascript and XML (AJAX) request, RSS feed, or in passing complex data to and from a web application.</p>
<p>Parsing XML data varies from language to language. In JavaScript, for instance, XML data are parsed by creating an instance of ActiveXObject for Internet Explorer or XMLHttpRequest otherwise. An effective way of doing so in PHP is by converting XML data to array using xml2array()*.</p>
<pre class="brush: php; title: ; notranslate">
function xml2array($xml) {
   $arXML = array();
   $arXML['name'] = trim($xml-&gt;getName());
   $arXML['value'] = trim((string)$xml);
   $t = array();
   foreach($xml -&gt; attributes() as $name =&gt; $value){
      $t[$name] = trim($value);
   }
   $arXML['attr'] = $t;
   $t=array();
   foreach($xml -&gt; children() as $name =&gt; $xmlchild) {
      $t[$name][] = xml2array($xmlchild); //FIX : For multivalued node
   }
   $arXML['children'] = $t;
   return($arXML);
}</pre>
<p>The code snippet above accepts a PHP SimpleXMLElement object and converts it to an associative array.</p>
<p><strong>Sample Usage:</strong></p>
<pre class="brush: php; title: ; notranslate">
   $xml = file_get_contents(&quot;http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/feed/rss&quot;);
   $xml_array = xml2array(new SimpleXMLElement($xml));</pre>
<p>*<small><a href="http://php.net/manual/en/book.simplexml.php" target="_blank">http://php.net/manual/en/book.simplexml.php</a></small></p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-converting-xml-to-array font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
