		<title>Mozilla released the latest Firefox Aurora for testing</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/mozilla-released-the-latest-firefox-aurora-for-testing</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/mozilla-released-the-latest-firefox-aurora-for-testing#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 05 Jun 2011 02:21:44 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Softwares]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Firefox]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Firefox Aurora]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[web browser]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=500</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/mozilla-released-the-latest-firefox-aurora-for-testing"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/firefox-aurora-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="firefox-aurora" /></a>Mozilla Firefox has recently moved to a rapid release development process to deliver new updates and releases of the popular browser to users faster giving Firefox four development stages: Nightly, Aurora, Beta, and Release. Nightly test builds – Includes features not tested by Mozilla QA Aurora channel &#8211; Enables users test the latest features and innovations Firefox Beta – Broadly test the stability of new features and improvements in the next version of Firefox Firefox Final Release – Delivers the[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="Firefox Aurora" rel="lightbox" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/firefox-aurora.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-501" title="firefox-aurora" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/firefox-aurora.jpg" alt="" width="259" height="194" /></a></p>
<p>Mozilla Firefox has recently moved to a rapid release development process to deliver new updates and releases of the popular browser to users faster giving Firefox four development stages: Nightly, Aurora, Beta, and Release.</p>
<ul>
<li>Nightly test builds – Includes features not tested by Mozilla QA</li>
<li>Aurora channel &#8211; Enables users test the latest features and innovations</li>
<li>Firefox Beta – Broadly test the stability of new features and improvements in the next version of Firefox</li>
<li>Firefox Final Release – Delivers the polished and stable features in Firefox to hundreds of millions of users</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Latest Firefox Aurora Now Available</strong></p>
<p>Mozilla has released the latest Firefox Aurora for testing. New features* enable users and web developers take more control over their browsing and development environments with improved overall performance which include the following:</p>
<ul>
<li>Data Management Window &#8211; is an experimental feature that provides control over the the access that specific websites have to your browsing data, including cookies, passwords and location information. To start testing this feature type “about:permissions” in the Awesome Bar (URL Bar)</li>
<li>Add-ons Manager with Plugin Check  -  quickly verifies the compatibility of installed plugins directly from the Add-Ons Manager</li>
<li>Panorama Groups on Demand &#8211; improves browser startup time and overall experience by allowing power Panorama users to load saved tab groups only when using Panorama</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>New Tools for Web Developers</strong></p>
<p>New set of web development tools* are also made available especially for developers including:</p>
<ul>
<li>The Scratchpad &#8211; lets developers quickly build and test JavaScript snippets in the browser</li>
<li>Web Console &#8211; adds the ability to move the console to other parts of the window or break out into a separate window</li>
<li>Web Developer Menu provides access to developer tools from the Firefox Aurora Menu Button</li>
</ul>
<p>Along with the new features and set tools, the latest Firefox Aurora has also additional support for HTML5, DOM level 3, server-sent events, networking technologies and other tools that make it easier for developers build advanced web applications.</p>
<p>Download the latest Firefox Aurora <a href="http://www.mozilla.com/en-US/firefox/channel/">here</a>.</p>
<p>* <small>http://blog.mozilla.com/futurereleases/2011/05/27/firefoxaurora/</small></p>
