		<title>Worpress 3.2 Beta 2</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/worpress-3-2-beta-2</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/worpress-3-2-beta-2#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 31 May 2011 22:44:22 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Wordpress]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Wordpress 3.2 Beta 1]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Wordpress 3.2 Beta 2]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=475</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/worpress-3-2-beta-2"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/wordpress-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="Wordpress" /></a>The development of WordPress&#8217; new version continues right on schedule. A couple of weeks after the release of WordPress 3.2 Beta 1, the popular blogging tool and publishing platform announces the release Beta 2. (Click here to read related post). Once again, since it is still in a development stage, it is not yet recommended (as all other software manufacturers do when their product is still a beta version) that you use it in a running site. Below are the[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="Worpress" rel="lightbox" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/wordpress.jpg"><img class="aligncenter" title="Wordpress" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/wordpress.jpg" alt="" width="238" height="212" /></a></p>
<p>The development of WordPress&#8217; new version continues right on schedule. A couple of weeks after the release of WordPress 3.2 Beta 1, the popular blogging tool and publishing platform announces the release Beta 2. (Click <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wordpress-3-2-beta-1">here</a> to read related post). Once again, since it is still in a development stage, it is not yet  recommended (as all other software manufacturers do when their product  is still a beta version) that you use it in a running site.</p>
<p>Below are the changes made since the release of WordPress 3.2 Beta 1:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://code.google.com/chrome/chromeframe/">Google Chrome Frame</a> is now supported in the admin, if you have it installed. This is  especially useful for IE 6 users (remember, IE 6 is otherwise deprecated  for the admin)</li>
<li>Aesthetic fixes specially made for IE7</li>
<li>The blue admin color scheme has caught up to the grey one, and is ready for testing</li>
<li>Beta 2 is now bundled with jQuery 1.6.1</li>
</ul>
<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/wordpress-3.2-beta2.zip">Download WordPress 3.2 Beta 2</a></p>
<p>WordPress 3.2 is expected to be released by June.</p>
