		<item>
		<title>PHP Snippets: Sending emails</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-sending-emails</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-sending-emails#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 30 May 2011 23:56:38 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[electronic direct mail]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[email]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP Snippets]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[sending emails]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=471</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-sending-emails"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="PHP" /></a>An electronic direct mail (EDM) or simpy email is a powerful tool in communicating with your site users. This is of great use, for example, in confirming them of their registration, sending them instructions on how to reset their password, notifying them of your site maintenance, or to announce a new feature on your website. Email feature on a website is also essential for newsletter subscriptions and other opt-in service that you offer requiring user&#8217;s email address. A number of[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="PHP" rel="lightbox" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png"><img class="aligncenter" title="PHP" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" alt="" width="184" height="113" /></a></p>
<p>An electronic direct mail (EDM) or simpy email is a powerful tool in communicating with your site users. This is of great use, for example, in confirming them of their registration, sending them instructions on how to reset their password, notifying them of your site maintenance, or to announce a new feature on your website. Email feature on a website is also essential for newsletter subscriptions and other opt-in service that you offer requiring user&#8217;s email address.</p>
<p>A number of open-source classes are made available over the net for web developer&#8217;s use. One of which, and probably the most popular among PHP developers, is <a href="http://phpmailer.worxware.com/" target="_blank">PHPMailer</a>. PHPMailer is produced by Brent R. Matzelle (original author), Andy  Prevost (project administrator), Patrice Fournier, Chris Ryan, Cem  Hurturk, Tom Klingenberg and Jaime Bozza and is a powerful email transfer class for PHP. That&#8217;s it for now about PHPMailer. Will talk more about it in my coming posts about sending emails.</p>
<p>This post will show you how to send emails simply by calling the mail() PHP function.</p>
<p><strong>The Syntax:</strong></p>
<pre><code>bool mail ( string <tt>$to</tt> , string <tt>$subject</tt> , string <tt>$message</tt> [, string <tt>$additional_headers</tt> [, string <tt>$additional_parameters</tt> ]] )</code></pre>
<p>This function simply returns true if the email has been successfully sent to the recipient, false otherwise. This requires SMTP service installed and enabled on your server which, most of the time, is by default on most servers.</p>
<p><strong>Example Usage:</strong></p>
<pre><code>&lt;?php 

   $sent = mail("user@domain.com", "Testing", "Hello, I'm testing this cool function from PHP");
   if($sent) {
      echo "Email has been successfully sent!";
   } else {
      echo "Oops! There seems to be a problem in sending the email";
   }

?&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>If you want to customize, say for example, the sender name or email, you may overwrite the default $additional_headers value.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-sending-emails font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
