		<item>
		<title>Creating MySQL Trigger</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/creating-mysql-trigger</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/creating-mysql-trigger#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 29 May 2011 01:58:59 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Softwares]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[MySQL]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[MySQL TRIGGER]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=465</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/creating-mysql-trigger"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/mysql-logo-300x218.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="MySQL" /></a>Sometimes, you need to retrieve information for a data in one of your MySQL tables contained in a separate table.  For example, getting the number of comments posted for a particular article, calculating the average rating, computing the total score of a user and so on. While joining MySQL tables or using subqueries can retrieve the data you wanted to get, it sometimes affect the performance of your system, application or website especially when there are several thousands of records[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="MySQL" rel="lightbox" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/mysql-logo-300x218.jpg"><img class="aligncenter" title="MySQL" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/mysql-logo-300x218.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="218" /></a></p>
<p>Sometimes, you need to retrieve information for a data in one of your MySQL tables contained in a separate table.  For example, getting the number of comments posted for a particular article, calculating the average rating, computing the total score of a user and so on. While joining MySQL tables or using subqueries can retrieve the data you wanted to get, it sometimes affect the performance of your system, application or website especially when there are several thousands of records involved. This will work if you have small amount of records to join and you are confident that it won&#8217;t reach a thousand records or so. If you are conscious about your site or application performance in terms loading times, you should be wary about the consequences when your number of users increases significantly.  It&#8217;s always a best practice to consider user experience.</p>
<p>You can get rid of joining tables or making MySQL subqueries by adding a field that will hold the information you wanted to achieve from doing so. Since the method drops the need for your query to calculate or retrieve some other information from another table, it will significantly lessen the time to take in executing your query resulting in an optimized site or application performance.</p>
<p>The new field gets updated everytime a new insert to the table it is related to is done. For example you have a <em>comments </em>table wherein all comments to all types of post like articles, podcast and so on are saved in and you have <em>comment_count </em>field in your <em>article </em>table that contains the number of rows in your <em>comments </em>table for a specific row of your <em>article </em>table. The updating process can be achieved automatically by using MySQL Trigger.</p>
<p><strong>What is a MySQL Trigger?</strong></p>
<p>A trigger is a named       database object that is associated with a table, and that       activates when a particular event occurs for the table. The       trigger becomes associated with the table named <em> table_name</em>, which must refer to a       permanent table (<em>http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.0/en/create-trigger.html</em>).</p>
<p><strong>The Syntax</strong></p>
<pre><code>CREATE
    [DEFINER = { <em><code>user</code></em> | CURRENT_USER }]
    TRIGGER <em><code>trigger_name</code></em> <em><code>trigger_time</code></em> <em><code>trigger_event</code></em>
    ON <em><code>tbl_name</code></em> FOR EACH ROW <em><code>trigger_body</code></em></code></pre>
<p><strong>Example</strong></p>
<pre><code>delimiter |

CREATE TRIGGER view_trigger BEFORE INSERT ON tbl_views
FOR EACH ROW BEGIN
 UPDATE tbl_blogs SET views = views + 1 WHERE blog_id = NEW.field_value;
 END;
|</code></pre>
<p><strong>Example Explained</strong></p>
<p>In the example above, we have <em>tbl_views</em> and <em>tbl_blogs</em> involved. A trigger (<em>view_trigger</em>) is created that activates everytime an insert is done to the <em>tbl_views</em> table which updates the views column of the <em>tbl_blogs</em> table incrementing it&#8217;s current value by 1. The specific record to update is determined by the value inserted in the <em>field_value</em> field of the <em>tbl_views</em> table.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/creating-mysql-trigger font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/creating-mysql-trigger/feed</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>3</slash:comments>
