		<category><![CDATA[PHP Snippets]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=436</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-identifying-content-type-of-a-file"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="PHP" /></a>For the force download script to work properly, you need to know the content type of the file you want to make downloadable. (Click here to read the related post). This post will show how to determine the content type of any file. &#60;form method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data"&#62; Select a file: &#60;input type="file" name="sample" /&#62; &#60;input type="submit" name="submit" value="Get Content Type" /&#62; &#60;/form&#62; &#60;?php if($_POST) { if($_FILES) echo "Content Type: " . $_FILES['sample']['type']; else echo "No file selected"; } ?&#62; The code[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" rel="lightbox" title="PHP"><img class="aligncenter" title="PHP" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" alt="" width="184" height="113" /></a></p>
<p>For the force download script to work properly, you need to know the content type of the file you want to make downloadable. (Click <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-a-force-download-script">here</a> to read the related post). This post will show how to determine the content type of any file.</p>
<pre><code>&lt;form method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data"&gt;
 Select a file: &lt;input type="file" name="sample" /&gt;
 &lt;input type="submit" name="submit" value="Get Content Type" /&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;

&lt;?php 
 if($_POST) {
    if($_FILES)
       echo "Content Type: " . $_FILES['sample']['type'];
    else 
       echo "No file selected";
  }
?&gt;</code></pre>
<p>The code snippet above gets the content type of the file through the &#8216;type&#8217; index of  $_FILES. We first create a form with a file input to be able us to browse a file.  After a simple check whether the submit button is checked, we then display the file&#8217;s content type if the input file is not empty.</p>
<p>Click <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/samples/content-type.php">here</a> to see the live demo.</p>
