		<title>PHP Snippets: Creating a force download script</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-a-force-download-script</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-a-force-download-script#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sun, 22 May 2011 22:44:14 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[force download]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=433</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-a-force-download-script"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="PHP" /></a>A force download script in PHP allows your users to download a specific file (e.g., an image file, audio file or even a video). Instead of being opened on a user&#8217;s browser, the force download page activates the download dialog box that lets them choose whether to save the file on their local machine or to open it with a compatible software. In PHP, this can be achieved by modifying the headers. This requires you to identify the content-type of[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="PHP" rel="lightbox" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png"><img class="aligncenter" title="PHP" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" alt="" width="184" height="113" /></a></p>
<p>A force download script in PHP allows your users to download a specific file (e.g., an image file, audio file or even a video). Instead of being opened on a user&#8217;s browser, the force download page activates the download dialog box that lets them choose whether to save the file on their local machine or to open it with a compatible software.</p>
<p>In PHP, this can be achieved by modifying the headers. This requires you to identify the content-type of the file you want to be made downloadable. The code snippet below shows you a sample on how to do it:</p>
<pre><code>header('Content-Type: application/octet-stream');
header('Content-disposition: attachment; filename=filename.zip');
readfile('filename.zip');</code></pre>
<p>This one is used in my previous post talking about creating zip files via PHP on the fly. (Click <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-zip-file">here</a> to read the post).</p>
<p><strong>Snippet Explained:</strong></p>
<p>First, as I have mentioned earlier, you need to know the content type of the file you want your users to download. Feed it in the content-type PHP header.</p>
<pre><code>header('Content-Type: application/octet-stream');</code></pre>
<p>Next, you want to activate to activate the download box instead of having the file read within the browser so you need to modify the content-disposition header to be attachment. You then specify the filename you want to label the downloadable file with. This is not necessarily has to be the same as the actual filename &#8211; you can choose a different one.</p>
<pre><code>header('Content-disposition: attachment; filename=filename.zip');</code></pre>
<p>Finally, read the physical file. If the file resides on a different location as your download script, you should include the its path.</p>
<pre><code>readfile('filename.zip');</code></pre>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-a-force-download-script font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
