		<title>Firebug 1.7.1</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/firebug-1-7-1</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/firebug-1-7-1#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 20 May 2011 23:09:14 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[CSS]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Firebug]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Firebug 1.7.1]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[HTML]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[JavaScript]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=424</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/firebug-1-7-1"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/firebug-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="Firebug" /></a>What is Firebug? Firebug is a Firefox addon that lets web developers edit (though this won&#8217;t be reflected to other site users), debug and monitor HTML, CSS and JavaScript live on any webpage.  Here are some of the things a a web developer can do with Firebug: Inspect and edit HTML. Firebug gives information about HTML elements and lets you edit them live. Tweak CSS. You can make changes with your styles to make your page look the way you[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/firebug.jpg" rel="lightbox" title="Firebug"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-425" title="Firebug" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/firebug.jpg" alt="" width="211" height="168" /></a></p>
<p><strong>What is Firebug?</strong></p>
<p>Firebug is a Firefox addon that lets web developers edit (though this won&#8217;t be reflected to other site users), debug and monitor HTML, CSS and JavaScript live on any webpage.  Here are some of the things a a web developer can do with Firebug:</p>
<ul>
<li><em>Inspect and edit HTML.</em> Firebug gives information about HTML elements and lets you edit them live.</li>
<li><em>Tweak CSS.</em> You can make changes with your styles to make your page look the way you want it.</li>
<li><em>Visualize CSS metrics.</em> Firebug is useful in editing containers when they loose alignment.</li>
<li><em>Monitor network activity.</em> Keep track of your site&#8217;s performance in terms of page load and know which part is making your page to take a long time loading.</li>
<li><em>Debug and profile JavaScript.</em> Firebug includes a powerful JavaScript debugger that lets you pause  execution at any time and have look at the state of the world.</li>
<li><em>Quickly find errors.</em> When you have errors in your JavaScript code, XML or even CSS, Firebug will give you a comprehensive error message to help you fix them.</li>
<li><em>Logging for JavaScript.</em> This is useful if you are debugging a live site and you just want to display a small piece of data that is not visible to other users.</li>
</ul>
<p>The latest version of the popular and powerful web development tool is 1.7.1 which fixes some issues reported from its last stable release &#8211; 1.7.  This is supposed to be the last maintenance version of Firebug and is reported that theFirebug Working Group (FWG) is concentrating in the development of Firebug 1.8.</p>
<p>To get the latest version of the tool or to learn more about the Firebug, click <a href="http://getfirebug.com/" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>
