		<title>PHP Snippets: Getting the current URL</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-getting-the-current-url</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-getting-the-current-url#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 18 May 2011 17:50:54 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[current page]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[current URL]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=412</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-getting-the-current-url"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="PHP" title="PHP" /></a>As of this writing, up to latest version PHP, it doesn&#8217;t have a predefined function that pulls the page (the absolute URL) that a user is currently viewing. Sometimes, you need this piece of string for some reason say, you want to share the link to social networking site programmatically, or to a blog site for that matter. The code snippet below will show you how to do it: &#60;?php function get_current_url() { $url = 'http'; if ($_SERVER["HTTPS"] == "on")[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="PHP" rel="lightbox" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png"><img class="aligncenter" title="PHP" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" alt="PHP" width="184" height="113" /></a></p>
<p>As of this writing, up to latest version PHP, it doesn&#8217;t have a predefined function that pulls the page (the absolute URL) that a user is currently viewing. Sometimes, you need this piece of string for some reason say, you want to share the link to social networking site programmatically, or to a blog site for that matter. The code snippet below will show you how to do it:</p>
<pre>&lt;?php
function get_current_url() {
 $url = 'http';
 if ($_SERVER["HTTPS"] == "on") {
    $url  .= "s";
 }
 $url .= "://";
 if ($_SERVER["SERVER_PORT"] != "80") {
    $url .= $_SERVER["SERVER_NAME"] . ":" . $_SERVER["SERVER_PORT"] . $_SERVER["REQUEST_URI"];
 } else {
    $url .= $_SERVER["SERVER_NAME"] . $_SERVER["REQUEST_URI"];   
 }
 return $url;
}
?&gt;</pre>
<p><strong>Snippet Explained:</strong></p>
<p>First, we declare a variable $url to hold the value that we will return at the end of the function and have it initialized to be &#8216;http&#8217; which is the start of a standard URL.</p>
<pre>$url = 'http';</pre>
<p>We now check if the current page uses secure HTTP. If it is, then we append &#8216;s&#8217; to the current value of $url. Otherwise, do nothing.</p>
<pre>if ($_SERVER["HTTPS"] == "on") {
    $url  .= "s";
 }</pre>
<p>Next is to append &#8216;://&#8217; which can be achieved by this line of code.</p>
<pre>$url .= "://";</pre>
<p>We then check if the page uses a port number other than 80 (the default). We will append that port to $_SERVER['SERVER_NAME']* and $_SERVER['REQUEST_URI']** to $url if it&#8217;s other than 80.</p>
<pre>if ($_SERVER["SERVER_PORT"] != "80") {
    $url .= $_SERVER["SERVER_NAME"] . ":" . $_SERVER["SERVER_PORT"] . $_SERVER["REQUEST_URI"];
 } else {
    $url .= $_SERVER["SERVER_NAME"] . $_SERVER["REQUEST_URI"];   
 }</pre>
<p>Finally, we return whatever is the value of $url.</p>
<pre>return $url;</pre>
<p><small>* <em>The name of the server host under which the current script is        executing. (http://www.php.net/manual/en/reserved.variables.server.php)</em><br />
** <em>The URI which was given in order to access this page (http://www.php.net/manual/en/reserved.variables.server.php)</em></small></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-getting-the-current-url font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
