		<item>
		<title>PHP Snippets: Creating zip files</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-zip-file</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-zip-file#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 17 May 2011 00:52:53 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Jason Stockton]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Peter Listiak]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[zip file]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[zip_min.inc]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=394</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-zip-file"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="PHP" title="PHP" /></a>If you have multiple files on your website that you want users to have them downloaded, you should provide a way such that your downloaders can download all of them on a single click. You may think of compressing or zipping the files first, upload it on your server and linking the path of the zip file to a specific download button or something. But what if the files grow dynamically, say a new file needs to be included in[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="PHP" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png rel="><img class="aligncenter" title="PHP" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" alt="PHP" width="184" height="113" /></a></p>
<p>If you have multiple files on your website that you want users to have them downloaded, you should provide a way such that your <em>downloaders</em> can download all of them on a single click. You may think of compressing or <em>zipping</em> the files first, upload it on your server and linking the path of the zip file to a specific download button or something. But what if the files grow dynamically, say a new file needs to be included in every single day? Repeating the process everytime can be cumbersome on your part. The solution? Create zip file on-the-fly using PHP.</p>
<p>You need to include a PHP library modified and packaged by Jason Stockton which was based on a patch made by Peter Listiak for last modified date and time of the compressed file (links provided in the source code).</p>
<pre>&lt;?php include_once('zip_min.inc'); ?&gt;</pre>
<p>Instantiate the zip class to create an object.</p>
<pre>&lt;?php $zip = new zipfile(); ?&gt;</pre>
<p>Now that you have your zip object ($zip), you can now do the <em>zipping</em> by adding files on the buffer using the addFile() method of the zip class.</p>
<pre>&lt;?php $zip-&gt;addFile(file_get_contents(file_to_copy), new_file_name); ?&gt;</pre>
<p>Output the zip file as downloadable file by modifing PHP headers:</p>
<pre>header('Content-Type: application/octet-stream');
header('Content-disposition: attachment; filename=filename.zip');
echo $zip-&gt;file();</pre>
<p>You may download zip.min.inc <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/download.php">here</a>.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-creating-zip-file font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
