				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Wordpress]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Wordpress 3.2 Beta 1]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=356</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wordpress-3-2-beta-1"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/wordpress-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="wordpress" /></a>Exactly 2 days ago when I wrote a post about WordPress, one of the most popular blogging tool and publishing platform (click here to read related post) talking about how to change the post author or force publish a scheduled blog entry. I am writing again about WordPress this time talking about the new version of the blogging tool. Weeks after releasing version 3.1.2, WordPress 3.2 is now available for beta testing. Of course, since it is still in a[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/wordpress.jpg" rel="lightbox" title="Wordpress"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-329" title="wordpress" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/wordpress.jpg" alt="" width="238" height="212" /></a></p>
<p>Exactly 2 days ago when I wrote a post about WordPress, one of the most popular blogging tool and publishing platform (click <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/changing-author-post-status-in-wordpress">here</a> to read related post) talking about how to change the post author or force publish a scheduled blog entry. I am writing again about WordPress this time talking about the new version of the blogging tool.</p>
<p>Weeks after releasing version 3.1.2, WordPress 3.2 is now available for beta testing. Of course, since it is still in a development stage, it is not yet recommended (as all other software manufacturers do when their product is still a beta version) that you use it in a running site. The new version is expected to be released by June.</p>
<p>Here are some of the new features in WordPress 3.2:</p>
<ul>
<li>Your blog will load faster thanks to the performance enhancements made for the new version</li>
<li>Full-screen mode in HTML view is now available<strong><br />
</strong></li>
<li>New Admin UI experience</li>
<li>New default theme</li>
<li>WordPress is made to work with modern browsers. If you visit your  Dashboard using an outdated web browser, it will let you know there’s a  newer version available.</li>
<li>More links on the admin bar</li>
</ul>
<p>And here are some points WordPress users should be aware of:</p>
<ul>
<li>The new version has a minimum system requirement: PHP 5.2.4 and MySQL 5.0</li>
<li>Microsoft Internet Explorer 6, popularly known as IE6, will no longer be supported</li>
<li>The favorites menu has been removed</li>
</ul>
<p>Click <a href="http://wordpress.org/wordpress-3.2-beta1.zip" target="_blank">here</a> to download WordPress 3.2 Beta 1.</p>
