		<title>JavaScript Snippets: Cross-browser keyboard event detection</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/javascript-snippets-cross-browser-keyboard-event-detection</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/javascript-snippets-cross-browser-keyboard-event-detection#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 10 May 2011 13:57:16 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[CSS]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[HTML]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[JavaScript]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[keyboard events]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=284</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/javascript-snippets-cross-browser-keyboard-event-detection"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/javascript-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="javascript" /></a>JavaScript has a wide range of functions that can deal with client interaction over the net like keyboard input, mouse clicks and so on. The challenge that developers often face, the same way as they do in HTML/CSS, is the compatibility of the functions with different browsers. This post will focus on detection of keyboard inputs regardless of the browser the user is using through the web&#8217;s client-side scripting language. Please take a look at the JavaScript snippet below: &#60;script[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="JavaScript" href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/javascript.jpg" rel="lightbox"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-285" title="javascript" alt="" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/javascript.jpg" width="267" height="189" /></a></p>
<p>JavaScript has a wide range of functions that can deal with client interaction over the net like keyboard input, mouse clicks and so on. The challenge that developers often face, the same way as they do in HTML/CSS, is the compatibility of the functions with different browsers. This post will focus on detection of keyboard inputs regardless of the browser the user is using through the web&#8217;s client-side scripting language. Please take a look at the JavaScript snippet below:</p>
<pre>&lt;script type="text/javascript"&gt;
   nn=(document.layers)?true:false;
   ie=(document.all)?true:false;

   function keyDown(e) {
      var evt=(e)?e:(window.event)?window.event:null;
      if(evt){
         var key=(evt.charCode)?evt.charCode:((evt.keyCode)?evt.keyCode:((evt.which)?evt.which:0));
         if(key == "13")
             alert("You just pressed ENTER");
         }
      }

   document.onkeydown=keyDown;
   if(nn) document.captureEvents(Event.KEYDOWN);
&lt;/script&gt;</pre>
<p>Click <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/samples/keyboard.html" target="_blank">here</a> for live code demo.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/javascript-snippets-cross-browser-keyboard-event-detection font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
