		<title>Adding Twitter box to your website</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/adding-twitter-box-to-your-website</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/adding-twitter-box-to-your-website#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 04 May 2011 13:22:06 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Twitter]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Twitter box]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Twitter widget]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=240</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/adding-twitter-box-to-your-website"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/twitter_logo-e1304515780663.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="twitter_logo" /></a>Keep your site viewers updated with your tweets by adding a Twitter widget on your website or blog. Adding twitter box on your website may also attract your readers and perhaps gaining more followers. This post will show you how it&#8217;s done. Sign in to your Twitter account. On the upper right corner of your Twitter page, click on your username to activate the dropdown and select Settings. On the Settings page, click on the Profile tab. Look for the[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/twitter_logo.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-247" title="twitter_logo" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/twitter_logo-e1304515780663.jpg" alt="" width="237" height="68" /></a></p>
<p>Keep your site viewers updated with your tweets by adding a Twitter widget on your website or blog. Adding twitter box on your website may also attract your readers and perhaps gaining more followers. This post will show you how it&#8217;s done.</p>
<ol>
<li>Sign in to your Twitter account.</li>
<li>On the upper right corner of your Twitter page, click on your username to activate the dropdown and select Settings.</li>
<li>On the Settings page, click on the Profile tab.</li>
<li>Look for the link that says &#8220;(You can also add Twitter to your site here)&#8221;. Clicking on the link will redirect you to a page that looks like the one below.  <a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/twitter.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-242" title="twitter" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/twitter-300x172.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="172" /></a></li>
<li>Select Widgets. On the Widgets page, Select My Website and choose the type of widget you wish to display on your website. You may choose any of the following:
<ul>
<li><strong>Profile Widget</strong> &#8211; Display your most recent Twitter updates on any webpage.</li>
<li><strong>Search Widget</strong> &#8211; Displays search results in real time! Ideal for live events,  broadcastings, conferences, TV Shows, or even just keeping up with the  news.</li>
<li><strong>Faves Widget</strong> &#8211; Show off your favorite tweets! Also in real time, this widget will pull  in the tweets you&#8217;ve starred as favorites. It&#8217;s great for moderation.</li>
<li><strong>List Widget </strong>- Put your favorite tweeps into a list! Then show &#8216;em off in a widget. Also great for moderation.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Customize your widget according to your preferences.</li>
<li>Click on Test Settings to preview your settings. Note, however, that dimension size don&#8217;t reflect on the widget preview.</li>
<li>Once satisfied, you may now copy the generated code and paste on the page you want Twitter box to be displayed in.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/adding-twitter-box-to-your-website font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/adding-twitter-box-to-your-website/feed</wfw:commentRss>
