		<title>PHP Snippets: Reading data from txt file</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-reading-data-from-txt-file</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-reading-data-from-txt-file#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 28 Apr 2011 15:36:49 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP Snippets]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=209</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-reading-data-from-txt-file"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="php" /></a>This post shows how to read data from a flat file (.txt) line per line. The code snippet below uses the explode() PHP function to put contents of the properly-delimited line of the txt file into an array. This is a perfect alternative for csv files especially if the data you are to read from exceeds the maximum number of rows that Excel can handle &#8211; about 65,000 rows. It is also more convenient because it doesn&#8217;t require any PHP[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-212" title="php" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/php.png" alt="" width="184" height="113" /></a></p>
<p>This post shows how to read data from a flat file (.txt) line per line. The code snippet below uses the explode() PHP function to put contents of the properly-delimited line of the txt file into an array. This is a perfect alternative for csv files especially if the data you are to read from exceeds the maximum number of rows that Excel can handle &#8211; about 65,000 rows. It is also more convenient because it doesn&#8217;t require any PHP library in extracting the contents of the file.</p>
<pre> &lt;?php 

   $handle = fopen("file.txt", "rb");
   $delimiter = ",";
   while (!feof($handle) ) {
        $line = fgets($handle);
        $data = explode($delimiter, $line);
        foreach($data as $v) {
            echo $v;
        }
    }
    fclose($handle);

 ?&gt;</pre>
<p><strong>Snippet Explained:</strong></p>
<p>First, we opened the flat the from which are data will be read from using the fopen() function. I assume you already are familiar with the different modes in opening files.</p>
<pre>$handle = fopen("file.txt", "rb");</pre>
<p>We then define our delimiter to separate each line to different fields. In this case we set it to comma(,).</p>
<pre>$delimiter = ",";</pre>
<p>Next, we loop through each line of the file contents, save the <em>exploded</em> data and display it.</p>
<pre>while (!feof($handle) ) {
        $line = fgets($handle);
        $data = explode($delimiter, $line);
        foreach($data as $v) {
            echo $v;
        }
    }</pre>
<p>Our final step is to close the reference to the opened file.</p>
<pre>fclose($handle);</pre>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-reading-data-from-txt-file font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/php-snippets-reading-data-from-txt-file/feed</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		</item>
		<item>
		<title>Convert batch (.bat) files to .exe</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/convert-batch-bat-files-to-exe</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/convert-batch-bat-files-to-exe#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Apr 2011 13:20:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Softwares]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technology]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[.bat to .exe]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[batch file to exe]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Quick Batch File Compiler]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Windows]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=202</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/convert-batch-bat-files-to-exe"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/qbc-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="Quick Batch File Compiler" /></a>Converting a regular batch file into an installer? Don&#8217;t be surprised, that would be possible through a simple compiler called Quick Batch File Compiler. As the name suggests, it is a fast way of turning your batch files into an executables (.exe). Not only does this program convert your .bat files into .exe, it also allows you to customize and change the default exe icon of your operating system, which in this case (most probably) is Windows, for your file.[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/qbc.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-203" title="Quick Batch File Compiler" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/qbc-300x190.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="190" /></a></p>
<p>Converting a regular batch file into an installer? Don&#8217;t be surprised, that would be possible through a simple compiler called Quick Batch File Compiler. As the name suggests, it is a fast way of turning your batch files into an executables (.exe). Not only does this program convert your .bat files into .exe, it also allows you to customize and change the default exe icon of your operating system, which in this case (most probably) is Windows, for your file. The only accepted format, however, for the executable icon is .ico but don&#8217;t worry, there&#8217;s a number of online converters out there just in case you don&#8217;t have photo editing softwares installed on your machine.</p>
<p>If you already have Quick Batch File Compiler installed on your computer, all you have to do is to right click the batch file you want to convert and click on &#8220;Compile with QBC&#8221; to launch the compiler. You then provide some information about the file (name, description, version, etc)</p>
<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/qbc-version-info.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-204" title="Quick Batch File Compiler version info" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/qbc-version-info-300x222.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="222" /></a></p>
<p>And customize your icon if you wan to</p>
<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/qbc-embedded-files.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-205" title="Quick Batch File Compiler embedded files" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/qbc-embedded-files-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a></p>
<p>Finally, click build to finish the conversion. You now have your exe file like with customized icon from a regular batch file.</p>
<p>You can download the latest version of Quick Batch File Compiler <a href="http://www.abyssmedia.com/quickbfc/" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/convert-batch-bat-files-to-exe font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
