		<title>json_encode for PHP 4</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/json_encode-for-php-4</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/json_encode-for-php-4#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Mon, 18 Apr 2011 16:11:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[JSON]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[json_encode]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=146</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/json_encode-for-php-4"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/JSON.gif" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="JSON" /></a>json_encode &#8211; returns the JSON representation of a value (http://php.net/manual/en/function.json-encode.php). This PHP function only works on servers running PHP 5.2.0 or later. What if you&#8217;re server only supports, say PHP 4.4? Don&#8217;t worry the code snippet below can handle that.  Thanks to Dzone Snippets! &#60;?php function json_encode($a=false) { if (is_null($a)) return 'null'; if ($a === false) return 'false'; if ($a === true) return 'true'; if (is_scalar($a)) { if (is_float($a)) { // Always use "." for floats. return floatval(str_replace(",", ".", strval($a)));[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/JSON.gif"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-147" title="JSON" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/JSON.gif" alt="" width="192" height="119" /></a></p>
<p>json_encode &#8211; returns the JSON representation of a value (http://php.net/manual/en/function.json-encode.php). This PHP function only works on servers running PHP 5.2.0 or later. What if you&#8217;re server only supports, say PHP 4.4? Don&#8217;t worry the code snippet below can handle that.  Thanks to <a href="http://snippets.dzone.com/posts/show/7487">Dzone Snippets</a>!</p>
<pre> &lt;?php
 function json_encode($a=false)
 {
    if (is_null($a)) return 'null';
    if ($a === false) return 'false';
    if ($a === true) return 'true';
    if (is_scalar($a))
    {
      if (is_float($a))
      {
        // Always use "." for floats.
        return floatval(str_replace(",", ".", strval($a)));
      }

      if (is_string($a))
      {
        static $jsonReplaces = array(array("\\", "/", "\n", "\t", "\r", "\b", "\f", '"'), array('\\\\', '\\/', '\\n', '\\t', '\\r', '\\b', '\\f', '\"'));
        return '"' . str_replace($jsonReplaces[0], $jsonReplaces[1], $a) . '"';
      }
      else
        return $a;
    }
    $isList = true;
    for ($i = 0, reset($a); $i &lt; count($a); $i++, next($a))     {       if (key($a) !== $i)       {         $isList = false;         break;       }     }     $result = array();     if ($isList)     {       foreach ($a as $v) $result[] = json_encode($v);       return '[' . join(',', $result) . ']';     }     else     {       foreach ($a as $k =&gt; $v) $result[] = json_encode($k).':'.json_encode($v);
      return '{' . join(',', $result) . '}';
    }
  }
?&gt;</pre>
<p>Hope this helps. Enjoy! Watch out for json_decode for PHP 4&#8230;</p>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/json_encode-for-php-4 font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
			<wfw:commentRss>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/json_encode-for-php-4/feed</wfw:commentRss>
		<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		</item>
