		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=13</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/automatically-change-users-facebook-status"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/plugins/thumbnail-for-excerpts/tfe_no_thumb.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="" /></a>The code snippet below shows how to automatically update the status of the of the user using your application. This technique is useful when you want to publish something on the user&#8217;s wall on his/her behalf without the need of having to logon to the application page itself. This will work even if the user is not online as long as he/she had granted your application to post to his/her wall and offline access as well. All you need to[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The code snippet below shows how to automatically update the status of the of the user using your application. This technique is useful when you want to publish something on the user&#8217;s wall on his/her behalf without the need of having to logon to the application page itself. This will work even if the user is not online as long as he/she had granted your application to post to his/her wall and offline access as well. All you need to do is setup an application, have the user grant your application with extended permissions and you&#8217;re all set.</p>
<pre>&lt;?php

 define(FACEBOOK_APP_ID, "Your Facebook App ID");
 define(FACEBOOK_SECRET, "Your Application Secret Key");

 $fb_userid = 'FB ID of the user the status will publish to';
 $message = "Your status message here";

 $code = $_REQUEST["code"];

 if(empty($code)) {
 $dialog_url = "http://www.facebook.com/dialog/oauth?client_id=" . FACEBOOK_APP_ID . "&amp;redirect_uri=" . urlencode($url)."&amp;scope=email,read_stream,offline_access,publish_stream&amp;response_type=token";
 echo("&lt;script&gt; window.top.location='" . $dialog_url . "'&lt;/script&gt;");
 }

 $access_token_url = "https://graph.facebook.com/oauth/access_token";
 $parameters = "type=client_cred&amp;client_id=" . FACEBOOK_APP_ID . "&amp;client_secret=" . FACEBOOK_SECRET;

 $access_token = file_get_contents($access_token_url . "?" . $parameters);

 $apprequest_url = "https://graph.facebook.com/feed";
 $parameters = "?" . $access_token . "&amp;message=" .urlencode($message) . "&amp;id=" . $fb_userid. "&amp;method=post";
 $result = file_get_contents($apprequest_url . $parameters);

 // output the post id
echo "post_id" . $result;

?&gt;<!--?php

    $url = "http://sayitbigph.com/cms";
    define(FACEBOOK_APP_ID, "113700015375491");
    define(FACEBOOK_SECRET, "12ff630b17101181a58f5613918b0523");

    $sched = $_GET['sched'];
    $sched_arr = explode("-", $sched);
    $sched = date("F d, Y", strtotime($sched_arr[0])) . " - " . date("F d, Y", strtotime($sched_arr[1]));

    $message = "I'm so excited! My personalized Mother's Day card to Mommy " . $_GET['mom'] . " has been approved and will be shown on large digital Billboards on EDSA from " . $sched . ". So watch out!";

	if($_GET['action'])
		$message = "Your guardian just confirmed your participation in SAY IT BIG . You can now start creating your personalized card for your Mommy! Click here to proceed http://apps.facebook.com/say-it-big/create-a-card.php";

    $code = $_REQUEST["code"];

    if(empty($code)) {
	    $dialog_url = "http://www.facebook.com/dialog/oauth?client_id=" . FACEBOOK_APP_ID . "&#038;redirect_uri=" . urlencode($url)."&#038;scope=email,read_stream,offline_access,publish_stream&#038;response_type=token";
	    echo("<mce:script type="text/javascript"--><!--  window.top.location='" . $dialog_url . "' // --></pre>
<p>This works as a regular post to wall except that it doesn&#8217;t include an image or a title &#8211; just a plain text. This mimics the ordinary status update plus an application icon at the bottom of the post.</p>
<p>Please take note, however, not to abuse publishing to the target&#8217;s wall  and be careful and cautious whatever it is that you want to post.</p>
