		<title>How to Check Fan Page Like From an Iframe Application</title>
		<link>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-check-fan-page-like-from-an-iframe-application</link>
		<comments>http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-check-fan-page-like-from-an-iframe-application#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Sat, 09 Apr 2011 15:43:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Web]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook application]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[iframe application]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[PHP]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/?p=4</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<a href="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-check-fan-page-like-from-an-iframe-application"><img align="left" hspace="5" width="150" height="150" src="http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/wp-content/plugins/thumbnail-for-excerpts/tfe_no_thumb.png" class="alignleft wp-post-image tfe" alt="" title="" /></a>This post shows how to check if the user viewing your Facebook Fan Page tab already has liked your page or not. In Static FBML fan page apps, you can achieve this by simply using the &#60;fb:visible-to-connection&#62; tag. Unfortunately, Facebook recently drops support for Static FBML so newly created fan pages are left with no choice but to stick to iframe applications. Anyway, let&#8217;s keep the ball rolling&#8230; First, just as all other Facebook Iframe Applications, you need to download[...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>This post shows how to check if the user viewing your Facebook Fan Page tab already has liked your page or not. In Static FBML fan page apps, you can achieve this by simply using the &lt;fb:visible-to-connection&gt; tag. Unfortunately, Facebook recently drops support for Static FBML so newly created fan pages are left with no choice but to stick to iframe applications. Anyway, let&#8217;s keep the ball rolling&#8230;</p>
<p>First, just as all other Facebook Iframe Applications, you need to download the Facebook PHP SDK.  Check it out here. <a href="https://github.com/facebook/php-sdk/" target="_blank">https://github.com/facebook/php-sdk/</a>. Include the sdk making sure you have specified the correct path to where the file is saved.</p>
<pre> &lt;?php include("facebook.php"); ?&gt;</pre>
<p>You may now instantiate the Facebook class using the following code snippet.</p>
<pre><code> &lt;?php

$facebook = new Facebook(array(
 'appId'  =&gt; 'Your app id',
 'secret' =&gt; 'Your api secret key',
 'cookie' =&gt; true, // enable optional cookie support
 ));

?&gt;</code></pre>
<p>Add the following code snippet to check if the user likes the fan page where the app is added to.</p>
<pre><code>&lt;?php

$signed_request = $_REQUEST["signed_request"];

list($encoded_sig, $payload) = explode('.', $signed_request, 2);

$data = json_decode(base64_decode(strtr($payload, '-_', '+/')), true);

$app_data = isset($data["app_data"]) ? $data["app_data"] : '';
$_REQUEST["fb_page_id"] = $data["page"]["id"];
$access_admin = $data["page"]["admin"] == 1;
$has_liked = $data["page"]["liked"] == 1;

?&gt;</code></pre>
<p>You may now use the $has_liked to separate your fan page <em>likers </em>from those who are not and display appropriate contents for them.</p>
<pre><code>&lt;?php

if($has_liked) {
   //display contents for fans
} else {
   //display contents for non-fans
}

?&gt;</code></pre>
<fb:like href=http://blogs.coldbuffer.com/how-to-check-fan-page-like-from-an-iframe-application font=></fb:like>]]></content:encoded>
